Part I - Loan Data from Prosper¶

by Peace Ugbekile¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains details of 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, borrower employment status, borrower credit history, and the latest payment information.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original dataset has 113,937 rows and 81 columns. However, I will be performing some data cleaning process based on my features of interest and it is expected that the final data structure will change. This will be communicated in the coming sections.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in understanding the major factors affecting people's ability to repay their loans captured by Loan Status, as well as attributes that adequately predict the borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR). Annual Percentage Rate (APR) refers to the annual cost of a loan to a borrower — including fees.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

To help with my investigation, the following are my variables of interest:

Main variables: Loan Status and Borrower APR

Predictors: Original Loan Amount, Term, Monthly Income, Borrower Rate, Prosper Score, Employment Status, Group Membership, Debt-to-income ratio and Income Range.

Here, I will be performing data cleaning process on the original dataset to reduce it to the number of interested variables.

Firstly, I will be creating a subset of my original dataset to include only the features I am interested in and storing them into a new dataframe called "newloan_data"

Some basic issues which I can identify in this dataset include missing values and wrong datatypes. The "ProsperScore" column has some null values, and there is no statistical justification for replacing null values for this particular variable since the values are uniquely assigned to borrowers ab initio. Therefore, I will be excluding rows with null values in this column. This will impact my overall dataset in terms of useful data for exploration.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

APR is negatively associated with loan amount, prosper score and monthly income. This means that as the loan amount increases, the APR decreases. Similarly, with an increase in prosper score comes a corresponding decrease in APR. Prosper Score is a measure of credit worthiness. This implies that higher prosper score means more credit worthiness and increased liklihood to pay down. This informs the decision of the lender to give a favorable APR to the borrower with such high credit worthiness. Furthermore, as monthly income increases, the chances of being credit worthy and completing repayment on loans increases. This is followed by a favorable consideration by the lender with respect to a reduced APR. credit risk to the lender. Therefore, a

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The correlation shown in the heat map describes a positive relationship between loan amount and monthly income. This shows that people who earn more are more liklely to access more funds in loans than those who earn less. Also, the heat map showed a negative correlation between debt-to-income (DTI) ratio and loan amount. DTI is a measure that compares earnings with monthly debt repayment. A high ratio is avoided by lenders. Therefore, the heat map shows that as the DTI increases, amount of loan to be accessed would decline and vice versa.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The relationship between APR and Loan Status was strengthened by loan term. Especially as it affects defaulters and past due obligations. Usually, lenders would want to carry out restructuring of loans for defaulters to help them pay down and this could be in the form of extending the term, reducing the interest rate or both. This graph clearly explains the principle of loan restructuring, where extended terms are given to defaulters alongside a reduction in APR to enable them pay down on these loans.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

No consistent pattern was observed in the relationship between APR and Prosper Score in the presence of loan Term.

Conclusions¶

This visualization process has revealed an interesting relationship between people's ability to complete their loan repayment and other factors. The main predictors of loan status as investigated were loan amount, monthly income and rate. Furthermore, I explored how factors like loan amount, monthly income and prosper score (which measures credit worthiness) affects borrower's annual percentage rate (APR). As a way to further understad relationships, a mediation effect was conducted on these relationships using loan tenure (Term) as a mediator.

The steps undertaken in this visualization include: Data gathering, Data assessing, Data cleaning, Univariate exploration, Bivariate exploration and Multivariate exploration
